</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ufenye.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Fenye</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Queen of Discord</span><br>  Posts: 637<br> <font color=#CC9900>(11/1/00 4:33:30 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Dorfs!</span><hr size=1> Here is the run down. I have a 52 paladin, a 35 bard and a 30 sk. You will prolly find this the best source of first hand info.<br>
<br>
Paladin - I really enjoyed playing the paladin from low levels, being a strong tank with healing powers, but paladins really shine when they hit level 39, as they get Greater Healing. Greater Healing is the same spell druids and shamans have until level 53. You also get some very nice buffs at level 49 (Valor, Guard and Symbol of Pinzarn). However, Paladins have insanely.. and I do mean incredibly hard quests. Paladins have it tough, such is thier style. They are also not as wanted for groups as much as the other hybrids.<br>
<br>
Bard - Incredibly fun to play. Yes, you need to have a good group to keep you alive, just like any other class. But I rarely die in groups (I die more often soloing than grouped) and their songs are extremely useful to groups, making them very desirable. Clarity song at 32, group invis at 19, very good melee buff songs (haste + stats) and hp regen songs. To put it one way, bards can do everything except teleport to other zones (yes, we can even teleport around the zone we are in), ressurect, and buff (those that stick, like Skin like Nature and such). The selo's line of travel songs will move you faster than Sow, and at 51 you get a new Selo's song that enables you to move faster than Spirit of the Cheetah. Bards are highly desirable for groups in places like sebilis, karnor's, fear planes (you get put in the KS groups alot.. hint hint), and dragon raids. Bards also have the lowest downtime of ALL the hybrids, as they do not need to meditate, and thier hp regen song takes care of any injuries. And you can kite.. without ever using mana! Everyone loves a bard!<br>
Though the only downside I can think of is learning how to twist songs effectively, and when to use instruments or weapons in certain situations. On the whole, I enjoy every aspect of my bard, while I only semi enjoy the paladin.<br>
<br>
Shadow Knight - Being evil is FUN. Depending on what race you pick, will decide if you are kos in certain zones or not. I have a human SK, and humans have a very nice INT (higher starting than the human paladins WIS, with the same STR base) coupled with a very nice STR base. They are also not as kos to other races as the Dark Elves, Ogres and Trolls. Kill a few crushbone orcs and you can go in Kelethin, Kaladim and even Felwithe. The major downside to the SK is the lack of power until level 30. Shadow Knights do not get thier first line of dots until level 30, so thier spell power really bites it hard until then. Having a pet is nice, but the SK pets are fairly weak until higher levels, and most of the time you will find that you will not need one unless you go soloing. Lifetaps are laughable until level 30, and you do not get invis until level 30 as well. Feign Death comes at level 30.. <br>
However, with a human SK, Deadeye becomes a very useful spell. Not only does it grant Ultravision, but also enables you to see invis. It's nice to the other races, but invaluable to a human sk. You gain this spell at level 22.<br>
Post 30 SKs are insanely powerful. Their Harm Touches are not as powerful as they used to be at lower levels, as the mob's HP becomes too much to make a big difference. But with the high level dots, bigger lifetaps, stronger pets, fear spells and Feign Death, you can truly solo and expect to survive. Unlike any of the other soloing caster classes, should you run oom, you can always fight your way out. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
Sk's have it very hard in the beginning, but the pay offs are well worth it.<br>
<br>
Overall summary - Paladins are fine.. if you like being second choice to other melee's. Make alot of friends and you should be fine finding groups, getting those hard quests finished, and getting your Valorium! Bards are about the funnest class to play, everyone loves you and they always tell ya, makes ya feel good. ShadowKnights have some initial problems, but really shine at higher levels. It just takes some hard work (or powerleveling :P ).<br>
<br>
<br>
Some STAT suggestions...<br>
<br>
Well, for paladins you should forget about STR, unless you choose High Elf. Having a base STR of 65 really needs some serious work, so I suggest putting 10 into STR, 5 into WIS and 5 into STA if a high elf. But no matter what race you pick, WIS is the most important. Higher levels you will need alot of wis to help out your clerics with the heals and buffs. STR and HP can always be buffed, but WIS is a hard stat to increase. Half Elves have a dead low wis, so dump almost all of your points into it, then some into STA or STR. Humans are great, they have average stats all around, so you can choice where you want to put your points. Dwarves are.. well. Dwarves have nice wis and str, but god.. they are ugly.<br>
<br>
Bards need charisma for thier charm and mes songs, and during most of your mid 20's to late 40's you will find your charm songs very useful, as it enables you to solo two or more mobs at once. Wood Elves have alot of dex and cha, so put more into STR and STA when creating one. Humans are always the same.. pretty even stats all around. Half Elves probably are about the same as humans, though you might want to dump a few into CHA and STA.<br>
<br>
Shadow Knights need alot of INT, like Paladins need WIS. STR isn't too important, as they can leech 10str off anything they want to. This is a level 9 spell. When making an Ogre or Troll SK, you will want to put all of your points into either INT, or STA/STR. Both have insanely low INT, and you will find that the double mana penalty on the lifetaps will be near useless to you if you don't have the mana for it. Though thier massive STR and STA is quite nice. Dark Elves have a very high INT, so put some into STR and STA, then if you want some into INT. <br>
<br>
<br>
